;the bottle&amp;quot;).
    Section heading preference If a noun phrase occurs in the heading of the section, part of which is the current sentence, then we consider it as the preferred candidate (1, 0).
    &amp;quot;Non-prepositional&amp;quot; noun phrases A &amp;quot;pure&amp;quot;, &amp;quot;non-prepositional&amp;quot; noun phrase is given a higher preference than a noun phrase which is part of a prepositional phrase (0, -1).
    Example: Insert the cassettei into the VCR making sure iti is suitable for the length of recording.
    Here &amp;quot;the VCR&amp;quot; is penalised (-1) for being part of the prepositional phrase &amp;quot;into the VCR&amp;quot;.
    This preference can be explained in terms of salience from the point of view of the centering theory.
    The latter proposes the ranking &amp;quot;subject, direct object, indirect object&amp;quot; (Brennan et al. 1987) and noun phrases which are parts of prepositional phrases are usually indirect objects.
